My GPA took a huge nosedive that semester. I really wanted to drop out afterwards but when your only other two options are working retail full time and going to the military...well, college it is. But if I could do things again...I would have chosen a major I was passionate about

I really wish I'd made my own major in college because I HATED my communications major and my GPA showed it. I still remember not going to class because it was the most boring class EVER....and subsequently getting an F...
And trying not to feel bad when I check out of meetings or class when it's boring...I thought I was just a rebel...

I've been relieved, happy and sad to know I have ADHD. Now it's about accepting it. It's a journey for sure, a process. Learning to laugh at myself when I do crazy things like leave my work laptop in another classroom I forgot I was in and not have it for HOURS...

but to find others like me, we have great laughs about so many of the crazy things we do because of ADHD...and cry because we thought we'd be further along and are frustrated with our lack of progress...

so I can definitely say...finding community with other folks who have ADHD has been THE BEST. I honestly thought so many of the things I do were things everyone did...and to find out they are ADHD things are hilarious...

I'll forever cherish these moments of teaching. All the gifts I got yesterday are a reminder that I may not be the best teacher but...my kids know I care and they care about me too.
Some of my kids who struggle the most honestly need me the most. And I'm facing an uphill battle with my colleagues about that...that's another story for another time...
Because those small moments of growth matter. If I make a HUGE deal of it...it can spur more growth.

And in this moment I realize that I LOVE my kids. I kept saying all year that these kids get on my nerves...and while it is true, my favorite moments are seeing that light bulb come on with them. My favorite moments are seeing my kids grow, even if it's only very small.

sidenote: finding my purpose is finally becoming...fun, dare I say it. it's felt crazy trying to navigate all of this the past decade plus years but...now that I'm close? Man. I can smell it. I can hear it. I can feel it.
And I think I just wrote part of my personal statement for graduate school just now!
I used to think education was the vehicle to lift us out of poverty. But truth be told, if we don't have our mental & emotional & physical well-being together, education will not save us.

Black women deserve to rest. We deserve to be well. We deserve to be whole. We deserve to laugh, and have joy, and play and be HAPPY. 
And Black kids deserve to have mothers who are happy.
I am leaving room for things to shift in my career as I grow, as I learn, but I do know...I've been passionate about black women and kids for a LONG time and I don't see that changing. AT ALL.

I want to  possibly focus on mental well-being, emotional well-being, and how the arts can play a central role in helping Black women be well. I want to be a clinician but I ALSO want to provide resources to those who may not be able to afford me.

So as I sit here working on my MSW application (and currently wondering if I need to do a dual MSW/MPH OR just do a doctorate in public health, which I think the latter will happen)...I'm wondering next, where am I needed? And where will the fun come for me?

And largely, the kids where I currently teach, their moms are overworked, because they have no choice. And I'm tired of seeing Black women working themselves to death and bragging about it. Tired of seeing angry black kids because that's all they see at home.
Mental Health. Aromatherapy. Rest. Retreat. Those are words that keep coming to me. Let's not pretend the wellbeing of our children isn't tied to the wellbeing of their caregivers.
Wellness. Black Women Wellness is what keeps coming to me, keeps being whispered to me.

Listening to the whispers of my ancestors this morning. 

What was whispered to me: 
Education alone will not save us.

I'm not mad at the need to be safe. Not mad at any of this at all. 

But the fallout of all of this...sucks.

Also, these kids don't know how to be in a classroom setting with their kids day in, day out. Alot of kids' pivotal development has taken place at home the last 1.5 years. The social interaction they would have gotten and NEEDED, was curtailed by the pandemic.
And when they were at home virtual, raising a virtual hand is nowhere near the same.

one thing I've realized when kids get up and throw stuff away in my class, talk out of turn, etc is that kids have been at home for FAR too long. They don't have to ask to go to the restroom, or throw something away or raise their hand.
This is temporary. Every bit of it. Yes I'm aware education will NEVER be the same but for right now? Teachers, we feel like we're teaching in the twilight zone. And who knows when it will end.
So maybe I come home these days a bit more calm because I know I'm not doing this work forever.

So even if they gave us a 20K raise? I would feel a little better but ultimately? I would still want to leave teaching. Because, this is not work that I love. This is not work that allows for teachers to be respected and revered and well taken care of.
Don't get me wrong, I'm thankful for the raise. But I think having to learn a new curriculum, teach more kids in a panini, learn technology, do more paperwork, etc is worth FAR more than 3%.

But also...I don't want to do all the work teachers do. If I didn't have to deal with RTIs, committees, and all the extra paperwork? Maybe teaching wouldn't be as bad. Every year they find a way to pile on more and give us a 3% raise.
My love language is MONEY. PAY ME WHAT I'M WORTH!

What have I learned about myself? I'm not passionate about teaching. I like kids, I like working with them...just not all day. It's exhausting. And I don't like feeling underappreciated, not valued, overworked and underpaid.
I'm learning to respond appropriately, depending on the situation.
I am QUICK with the comebacks and I'm learning to curb alot of that and respond with little to no emotion. Any kind of humor, frustration, anger, whatever? Kids react to that.

I'm learning that every teacher has to find their teacher voice. I'm learning that there are times to be witty and times to be concise with my words so I don't rile up students and they react, which creates a bigger disruption.

Right now, my classroom? That's still a lesson being learned, establishing a culture of respect. The moment kids decide to be disrespectful, honestly, that is a HUGE defining moment in a teacher's school year. Your response can make or break the year.

As a teacher...personality wise...I'm the witty, fun teacher who is learning that there's a time for [structured] fun and a time for drills...sometimes you can mix the two. But only after you've established alot of structure and a culture of respect in the classroom.
Professionally...I'm still trying to learn the ropes of school politics. I hate politics. I play, to a point. Thankfully, as a Leo rising...I can be quite charming LOL

I'm good at age appropriate rigor and student engagement. I'm good at listening. I'm also finding a balance between being an enforcer of all the rules and being flexible and taking things on a case by case basis. the INFP in me hates being the enforcer all the time.

Personally, if I can master my inner talk, and focus on my strengths? I'm a hell of a teacher. No I haven't seen massive gains in my kids scores. But I'm good at breaking things down so that my kids can understand.
Also, the longer I teach, there are just certain things I can anticipate. I have learned alot about myself personally and professionally.

2) Kids only do what they've learned from adults or what adults allow them to do. (I could be wrong, and I'm open to being wrong)

3) The pandemic has shed light on things and put alot in perspective for me, both personally and professionally.

My emotions are due to my experience and wisdom. Yes, I'm still an early career teacher but I've learned that: 1) kids will be kids, no matter where you go. They all face challenges, often exacerbated by socioeconomics, family dynamics, learning disabilities, and other things.
Now? I have an interesting mix of emotions.
My first few years of teaching almost every day felt like fight or flight. It was exhausting. Every day I came home feeling defeated, like I wanted to quit.
As soon as the kids leave, I exhale. I've made it through another day. And it's always a sigh of relief.

You come in and take a test after you've lost loved ones to COVID or other illnesses during a pandemic and maybe didn't even get a proper goodbye. See how you do.

We only want to address learning loss but not the actual loss of normalcy, or actual life. 

A slap in the face if you ask me.
I can already see a need for therapy for these kids, to help get them through the pandemic and beyond.

Yes kids are resilient, but they are still dealing with grief. 

Why is it not being addressed in the classroom? 

And why are we surprised many of these kids are cutting the fool in the classroom as a result?

We were NOT prepared to come back to school, face to face, in the middle of a pandemic.

Kids WILL grow if we give them room, sun, and water the seeds planted and we plant more. 

But the pressure to get them 'caught up' in a pandemic? 

Nah.

I'm not focused on getting them 'caught up.'

My kids WILL grow. But I'm not focused on getting them on grade level. I'm not Jesus. I can't perform those kinds of miracles. But I CAN get them the foundation of what they need to be proficient readers.

Many of my current fourth graders read on or below a second grade reading level. So, I can give them phonics instruction, and work heavily on the foundational reading skills. I can start there, while exposing them to fourth grade instruction.

I cannot go back and give them what they've 'missed.'

But I can give them what they need NOW.

So all the talk of learning loss, and catching up? We are gonna have to reframe our thinking around what our kids have 'missed' and what they 'need.'

I teach a population of kids that were already 'behind' before the pandemic.

Their second grade year was interrupted by COVID. Third grade was spent in and out of remote learning. 

I cannot go back and give them ALL of what they missed second and third grade.

My current fourth graders? Their last normal school year was first grade. 

Yes. FIRST GRADE.

And as educators we will have to accept that. 

Now, kids are resilient. Many educators are resilient as well. 

But we cannot make up lost ground the way we think we can for all of the instructional time (F2F and remote) that our kids have missed.

Also...I'm going to say something that may be unpopular. I may get unfollowed. I may get some replies that disagree. I'm okay with that. You ready? 

These kids will NEVER catch up.

So the word for this year, I thought it was SURVIVE as an educator (LBVS) but it's PIVOT. I'll be consistently pivoting as we get used to a new reality and a year full of changes until we FINALLY realize that education will never be the same as it was before.

ALOT of challenges already, but...again...as an educator, I'm realizing...change is inevitable. It's here. Things will never be the same. Pivot or leave the field. Pivot or leave kids behind. The latter is NOT an option IMO.

Teaching has been DIFFICULT this year so far. My kids came in with an October mindset. I hate that I have far more kids this year who have been previously retained than before and because of that, they're the ones who have already checked out...

We learned last year that we have to be ready to go virtual whenever, and also that when we do go virtual, remote learning and F2F learning cannot look the same so we will have to go back and forth between the two. Whew. exhausting.

3) If it turns into long term virtual instruction, again, certain crucial instructional decisions must be made. Everything doesn't translate virtually but it's my job as an educator to do the best I can to break things down so my kids still learn.

2) CRUCIAL instructional decisions must be made. I can't teach all the priority standards, but I can loop back around to things when we're virtual and reinforce what they've already learned. I'm not introducing new concepts for short virtual stints.

I'm already realizing as an educator, if the year will be on and off, with us going out at least 2-3 times...that's 2-3 crucial weeks of my pacing guide GONE. So...I'll have to pivot...and prioritize a few things...1) my kids' mental and emotional health as well as my own +
So. Personalized instruction will increase, and those who can afford to homeschool or get private tutors will. Those who cannot, will just continue to fall further behind. And, it sucks.

I've already seen some teachers who don't realize that when kids don't have internet access and there are no hotspots to be given, kids will fall behind and they just say 'oh well.'

That makes zero sense to me.
But to punish the kids? unfair.
Also, I will see a lack of sensitivity if it's not there already with these kids because, folks will blame the parents for not getting vaccinated or taking them around unvaccinated folks...
Because unless these kids get tutors, each kid without internet at home will fall behind each time we go out on quarantine or have to miss school because someone in their house has to quarantine...
not caring if kids have missed large chunks of school. and unless you strengthen internet infrastructure, the gap will widen between those who do well academically and those who don't.

for many, education will be interrupted for yet another year, off and on, with a lack of stability. And while some would say this should be a case to abolish standardized testing, I feel they will double down on testing kids and insist on it +
